22 (12 points) Let $f(x)=\frac{a}{\sim}+x \ln x, g(x)=x^{3}-x^{2}-3$.
(1) When $a=2$, find the equation of the tangent line to the curve $y=f(x)$ at $x=1$;
(2) If there exist $x_{1}, x_{2} \in[0,2]$ such that $g\left(x_{1}\right)-g\left(x_{2}\right) \geqslant M$ holds, find the largest integer $M$ that satisfies the above condition;
(3) If for any $s, t \in\left[\frac{1}{2}, 2\right]$ we have $f(s) \geqslant g(t)$, find the range of real numbers $a$.
